{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637330"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:41:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:41:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17648"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17648"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60968"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7804"},{"type":"tags","id":"7831"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a study comparing two different teaching methods for medical students. The study includes 15 students in each group. The researcher performs 20 different statistical tests comparing various outcomes between the groups. One comparison shows a statistically significant difference (p=0.04) in exam scores, with Group A scoring 2% higher than Group B.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the interpretation of these results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The sample size is adequate for reliable conclusions","The results require adjustment for multiple comparisons","The teaching method in Group A is definitively superior","The 2% difference represents a meaningful effect size","The p-value proves a true difference exists"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe results require \u003Cstrong\u003Eadjustment for multiple comparisons\u003C/strong\u003E due to the high number of statistical tests performed. When conducting multiple statistical tests, the chance of finding a significant result by chance alone increases. In this case, performing 20 tests with an alpha level of 0.05 means there is a high probability of at least one false positive result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect interpretations can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe teaching method in Group A is definitively superior\u003C/strong\u003E - A small 2% difference, while statistically significant, may not represent a meaningful educational difference\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe sample size is adequate for reliable conclusions\u003C/strong\u003E - 15 students per group is a relatively small sample size, which limits the reliability and generalisability of the findings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe 2% difference represents a meaningful effect size\u003C/strong\u003E - Statistical significance does not equate to practical or educational significance. A 2% difference in scores may be too small to be meaningful\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe p-value proves a true difference exists\u003C/strong\u003E - P-values indicate the probability of obtaining such results by chance, not proof of a true difference\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis example illustrates common pitfalls in statistical interpretation: over-reliance on p-values, failure to account for multiple comparisons, inadequate sample size, and conflating statistical significance with practical importance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Statistical significance (p\u003C0.05) does not always indicate clinical importance or meaningful effect size.","Multiple comparisons increase the likelihood of finding false positive results by chance.","Small sample sizes can lead to unreliable statistical conclusions even when p-values appear significant."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60968"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17648"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60968"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:41:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:55:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10362"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75458"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attrib